[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 73/100 path 2/3 answer="Step 1: Calculate the total number of lollipops sold by all students.\nNumber of students = 30\nLollipops sold per student = 10\n\nTotal lollipops sold = Number of students * Lollipops sold per student\n= 30 * 10 = 300 lollipops\n\nStep 2: Calculate the total revenue from selling the lollipops.\nCost price of each lollipop = $0.5\nRevenue from selling each lollipop = Cost price + Profit (which we need to calculate)\nSince we want to find out the profit first, let's denote it as P.\n\nPrice received by the seller = Total revenue / Total number of lollipops sold\nProfit made on each lollipop sale = Price received - Cost price\nP = $0.5\n\nSo, Revenue per lollipop = $0.5 + P\n\nNow, Total revenue = Revenue per lollipop * Total number of lollipops sold\n= ($0.5 + P) * 300\n\nStep 3: Calculate the total cost of buying the lollipops.\nCost of each lollipop = $0.5\nTotal cost of buying lollipops = Cost price * Total number of lollipops sold\n= $0.5 * 300\n\nStep 4: Calculate the net profit.\nNet profit = Total revenue - Total cost of buying lollipops\n\nSubstituting the values:\n\nNet profit = [($0.5 + P) * 300] - [$0.5 * 300]\n\nSince we don't have the exact value of P, we can simplify further:\nP = $0.5\nNet profit = ($0.5 + $0.5) * 300 - $"
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 73/100 path 3/3 start
