[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 88/100 path 3/3 answer='To determine how many books Bob can buy per school, we start by finding out the total number of books he can purchase with his budget.\n\nStep 1: Calculate the number of books Bob can buy with his entire budget.\n\\[ \\text{Number of books} = \\frac{\\text{Total budget}}{\\text{Cost per book}} = \\frac{27000}{500} = 54 \\]\n\nSo, Bob can buy a total of 54 books with his $27,000.\n\nStep 2: Determine the number of books he can buy from each school.\nSince he has 54 books and wants to distribute them equally among 3 schools:\n\\[ \\text{Books per school} = \\frac{\\text{Total books}}{\\text{Number of schools}} = \\frac{54}{3} = 18 \\]\n\nThus, Bob can buy 18 books per school.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 88/100 done id=gsm8k_test_1182 prediction='1800' gold='1800' correct=True vote_counts={'1800': 1, '18': 1, 'To determine how many books Bob can buy per school, we start by finding out the total number of books he can purchase with his budget.\n\nStep 1: Calculate the number of books Bob can buy with his entire budget.\n\\[ \\text{Number of books} = \\frac{\\text{Total budget}}{\\text{Cost per book}} = \\frac{27000}{500} = 54 \\]\n\nSo, Bob can buy a total of 54 books with his $27,000.\n\nStep 2: Determine the number of books he can buy from each school.\nSince he has 54 books and wants to distribute them equally among 3 schools:\n\\[ \\text{Books per school} = \\frac{\\text{Total books}}{\\text{Number of schools}} = \\frac{54}{3} = 18 \\]\n\nThus, Bob can buy 18 books per school.': 1}
