[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][mmlu] sample 5/100 path 3/3 answer="Calcium homeostasis involves regulation through various hormones and organs, including parathyroids, bones, kidneys, and calcitriol (active vitamin D). \n\n1. Parathyroid hormone increases blood calcium levels by activating osteoclasts to break down bone and releasing more calcium into the bloodstream.\n2. Calcitonin decreases blood calcium levels by inhibiting osteoclast activity and promoting uptake of calcium from bone.\n3. Vitamin D is synthesized by the skin upon exposure to sunlight and regulates calcium absorption in the intestines.\n\nGiven these mechanisms:\n\n- Option A suggests calcitonin raises calcium; however, it actually lowers calcium levels.\n- Option B states primary hyperparathyroidism has no symptoms, which contradicts known findings that patients often experience fatigue, anorexia, nausea, and muscle weakness.\n- Option C claims vitamin D is secreted by parathyroid glands, but vitamin D synthesis occurs elsewhere; it's produced in the skin.\n- Option D correctly identifies oliguria as a sign of hypercalcemia due to reduced renal excretion of calcium.\n\nThe correct answer is D."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][mmlu] sample 5/100 done id=mmlu_test_520 prediction='C' gold='B' correct=False vote_counts={'C': 2, "Calcium homeostasis involves regulation through various hormones and organs, including parathyroids, bones, kidneys, and calcitriol (active vitamin D). \n\n1. Parathyroid hormone increases blood calcium levels by activating osteoclasts to break down bone and releasing more calcium into the bloodstream.\n2. Calcitonin decreases blood calcium levels by inhibiting osteoclast activity and promoting uptake of calcium from bone.\n3. Vitamin D is synthesized by the skin upon exposure to sunlight and regulates calcium absorption in the intestines.\n\nGiven these mechanisms:\n\n- Option A suggests calcitonin raises calcium; however, it actually lowers calcium levels.\n- Option B states primary hyperparathyroidism has no symptoms, which contradicts known findings that patients often experience fatigue, anorexia, nausea, and muscle weakness.\n- Option C claims vitamin D is secreted by parathyroid glands, but vitamin D synthesis occurs elsewhere; it's produced in the skin.\n- Option D correctly identifies oliguria as a sign of hypercalcemia due to reduced renal excretion of calcium.\n\nThe correct answer is D.": 1}
