[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][mmlu] sample 12/100 path 1/3 answer='The kinetic energy \\( K \\) of an object is given by \\( K = \\frac{1}{2}mv^2 \\), where \\( m \\) is the mass and \\( v \\) is the velocity. Since we know that the uncertainty in the mass \\( \\Delta m \\) is negligible, we can consider the uncertainty in \\( v \\). \n\nGiven that the uncertainty in the measured speed \\( v \\) is 10%, if we denote the true speed as \\( v_{\\text{true}} \\), then:\n\\[ \\Delta v = 0.1v_{\\text{true}} \\]\n\nThe relative uncertainty in kinetic energy \\( K \\) due to the uncertainty in \\( v \\) can be calculated using the chain rule of differentiation:\n\\[ \\left( \\frac{\\Delta K}{K} \\right)^{-1} = 2 \\cdot \\left( \\frac{\\Delta v}{v} \\right) \\]\n\nSubstituting the value of \\( \\Delta v \\):\n\\[ \\left( \\frac{\\Delta K}{K} \\right)^{-1} = 2 \\cdot \\frac{0.1v_{\\text{true}}}{v_{\\text{true}}} \\]\n\\[ \\left( \\frac{\\Delta K}{K} \\right)^{-1} = 2 \\cdot 0.1 \\]\n\\[ \\left( \\frac{\\Delta K}{K} \\right)^{-1} = 0.2 \\]\n\nTaking the reciprocal to find the absolute error in \\( K \\):\n\\[ \\Delta K = K \\cdot 0.2 \\]\n\nSince the initial question asks about the uncertainty in the kinetic energy and does not specify a specific value for \\( K \\), we express the uncertainty directly proportional to \\( K \\).\n\nTherefore, the uncertainty in the kinetic energy of the ball is approximately twice'
