[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][mmlu] sample 16/100 path 1/3 answer="1. When a star collapses, it can form a black hole due to gravitational compression.\n2. Black holes have such strong gravity that nothing (including light) escapes from their event horizon.\n3. Assuming Earth were near a black hole during the collapse, tidal forces would pull on different parts of the planet differently.\n4. Given these conditions, both options B and C describe potential outcomes for our planet's fate if Earth were nearby during the solar system’s formation or evolution into a black hole scenario.\n5. Therefore, the correct answer is D - Both C and D."
