[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][mmlu] sample 17/100 path 1/3 answer="1. Gravitational waves travel through space at the speed of light.\n2. The speed of light is approximately \\(6 \\times 10^5\\) kilometers per second.\n3. One light-year is about 9.46 trillion kilometers.\n4. To find how long it takes for gravitational waves to travel 20 light-years, we multiply the distance by the speed of light and then convert it into time.\n\nCalculation:\n\\[ \\text{Time} = \\frac{\\text{Distance}}{\\text{Speed of light}} = \\frac{20 \\times 9.46 \\times 10^{12} \\text{ km}}{6 \\times 10^5 \\text{ km/s}} \\]\n\nLet's break down the calculation:\n\n\\[ \\text{Time} = \\frac{20 \\times 9.46 \\times 10^{12}}{6 \\times 10^5} \\]\n\\[ \\text{Time} = \\frac{20}{6} \\times \\frac{9.46 \\times 10^{12}}{10^5} \\]\n\\[ \\text{Time} = \\frac{10}{3} \\times 9.46 \\times 10^7 \\]\n\\[ \\text{Time} \\approx 3.3 \\times 10^8 \\text{ seconds} \\]\n\nConvert time to years:\n\\[ \\text{Time in years} = \\frac{3.3 \\times 10^8 \\text{ s}}{3.154 \\times 10^7 \\text{ s/year}} \\approx 10.43 \\text{ years} \\]\n\nConclusion:\nGravitational waves will take approximately 10.43 years to travel"
