[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][mmlu] sample 25/100 path 3/3 answer='1. **Identify the relevant chemical equation**: For a monoprotic acid (HA), the dissociation can be represented as HA ⇌ H⁺ + A⁻. When the solution contains both undissociated and dissociated forms of the acid, the concentration of hydrogen ions [H⁺] equals twice the concentration of undissociated acid because one molecule of HA splits into one H⁺ ion and one A⁻ ion.\n\n   \\[ \\text{Initial} & \\quad [\\text{HA}] = x \\\\\n   \\text{Equilibrium} & \\quad [\\text{H}^+] = 2x \\\\\n   \\]\n\n2. **Use the given pH to find [H⁺]**: The pH is 4.26, so \\([H^+]\\) = \\(10^{-pH}\\) = \\(10^{-4.26}\\).\n\n   \\[ [\\text{H}^+] = 10^{-4.26} \\approx 5.92 \\times 10^{-5} \\]\n\n3. **Calculate the concentration of undissociated acid** (\\(x\\)):\n\n\\[ 2x = 5.92 \\times 10^{-5} \\]\n\\[ x = \\frac{5.92 \\times 10^{-5}}{2} \\]\n\\[ x = 2.96 \\times 10^{-5} \\]\n\n4. **Find the Ka value from the equilibrium concentrations**:\n\n\\[ K_a = \\frac{[\\text{H}^+][\\text{A}^-]}{[\\text{HA}]} \\]\n\n\\[ K_a = \\frac{(5.92 \\times 10^{-5})(2.96 \\times 10^{-5})}{2.96 \\times'
