[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][mmlu] sample 37/100 done id=mmlu_test_4374 prediction='A' gold='A' correct=True vote_counts={'A': 2, 'Given equations are \\(a + b + c = 6\\), \\(ab + ac + bc = 5\\), and \\(abc = -12\\). We want to find \\(a^3 + b^3 + c^3\\).\n\nFirst, recall the identity for the sum of cubes:\n\\[a^3 + b^3 + c^3 - 3abc = (a+b+c)(a^2 + b^2 + c^2 - ab - ac - bc).\\]\n\nWe already know \\(a + b + c = 6\\) and \\(ab + ac + bc = 5\\). To find \\(a^2 + b^2 + c^2\\), we square \\(a + b + c\\):\n\\[\n(a + b + c)^2 = a^2 + b^2 + c^2 + 2(ab + ac + bc).\n\\]\nSubstituting the known values:\n\\[\n6^2 = a^2 + b^2 + c^2 + 2 \\cdot 5,\n\\]\n\\[\n36 = a^2 + b^2 + c^2 + 10,\n\\]\n\\[\na^2 + b^2 + c^2 = 26.\n\\]\n\nNow substitute into the sum of cubes formula:\n\\[\na^3 + b^3 + c^3 - 3(-12) = 6(26 - 5),\n\\]\n\\[\na^3 + b^3 + c^3 + 36 = 6 \\cdot 21,\n\\]\n\\[\na^3 + b^3 + c^3 + 36 = 126,\n\\]\n\\[\na^3 + b^3 + c^3 = 126 - 36,\n\\]\n\\': 1}
